comments.message:
Let's take an example without codegen: suppose we get a `Sensor` from redfish request:
```
{
  "@odata.id": "/redfish/v1/Chassis/1/Sensors/sensorX",
  "@odata.type": "#Sensor.v1_2_0.Sensor",
  "Id": "sensorX",
  "Name": "sensorX",
  "Reading": 12.077,
  "SparePartNumber": "XXX",
  "ReadingType": "Voltage",
  "ReadingUnits": "V",
  "Status": {
    "Health": "OK",
    "State": "Enabled"
  },
  "Thresholds": {
    "LowerCaution": {
      "Reading": 11.346
    },
    "LowerCritical": {
      "Reading": 11.224
    },
    "UpperCaution": {
      "Reading": 13.054
    },
    "UpperCritical": {
      "Reading": 13.176
    }
  }
  ...
}
```
Now, we want to extract specific value from such response,  there is two way we can do so.
First approach is to direct json access:
```
json sensor {jsonResponse};
if (sensor.is_object()){
  if (sensor.contains("Id")) {
    auto id = sensor["Id"].template get<string>();
    // do something with id 
  }
  if (sensor.contains("ReadingType")) {
    auto readingType = sensor["ReadingType"].template get<string>();
    // either direct compare the string to map it to a enum class   
  }
  if (sensor.contains("@odata.type")) {
    auto odataType = sensor["@odata.type"].template get<string>();
    auto version = getVersionFromOdataType(odataType);
    if (version > 1.9 && sensor.contains("SparePartNumber")) {
      // do something with spare part number
    }
  }
  if (sensor.contains("Thresholds") {
    auto thresholds = sensor["Thresholds];
    if (thresholds.is_object() && thresholds.contains("LowerCaution")) {
      // do something with lower caution
    }
  }
}
```
The other way is to write a custom class that can be serialized and deserialized from json:
```
Class Sensor;
...
json sensorJson = json::parse(jsonResponse);
Sensor sensor  = sensorJson.template get<Sensor>();
if (auto id = sensor.id(); id.hasValue()){
  // do something with id
}
if (auto readingType = sensor.readingType(); readingType.hasValue()){
  // readingType already a enum class, do something with it
}
if (auto sparePartNumber = sensor.sparePartNumber(); sensor.version() >= sensor.sparePartNumberVersionAdded() && sparePartNumber.hasValue()) {
  // do something with spare part number
}
if (auto thresholds = sensor.thresholds(); thresholds.has_value()) {
  if (auto lowerCaution = thresholds.lowerCaution(); lowerCaution.hasValue()) {
    // do something with lower caution
  }
}
```

Compare with these two approach, I believe the latter one should be preferred as it provides better abstraction to prevent duplicated and tedious code (like all the OOP benefit).

Now, in terms of writing the `Sensor` class, a human being would basically look at the redfish schema and translate its properties one-by-one to cpp class. This work is tedious, time consuming because there are roughly 2000+ unique class/typedef/enum/struct needed to written and in average 7 properties for each of those based on the latest redfish schema. Therefore, it would be much more efficient to write a lightweight codegen library that can take redfish schemas and turns into such data classes with static metadata (like which version is the property added/deprecated) filled in and correct dependency graph. In addition, whenever there is new version of redfish schema being published, we can just use the tool to target new set of schemas to generate class rather than having human being to figure out what change and change accordingly.

This approach does come with certain limitations, as it’s not as straightforward as it might initially appear. The focus shifts from writing code to configuring metadata for code generation, which can result in class structures with specific naming conventions that may be challenging for users to search and navigate. Furthermore, code editors might offer limited support in this case, as the code is generated in the build directory. (I’ve personally encountered this challenge while working with DBus code.)

In most cases, we are only interested in a small subset of the data within a schema, rather than the entire dataset. However, the code generation approach retrieves all the data, which can lead to memory and performance inefficiencies. Ideally, we should only incur costs for the data we actually use.


There is an alternative approach that hasn’t been mentioned.
```
    JsonSerializer val(jsonData);
    std::optional<double> CauReading;
    std::optional<double> CritReading;
    val.deserialize("Thresholds/LowerCaution/Reading", CauReading,
                    "Thresholds/LowerCritical/Reading", CritReading);
    if (CauReading)
    {
        //your stuff
    }
    if (CritReading)
    {
        //your stuff
    }
```
